metadata.name: Different Intersections - Iteration 4 #297
metadata.description:
This is the culmination of a series of iterations

____ - Iteration 1
____ - Iteration 2
____ - Iteration 3

The iterations were released under the pseudonym Extracurricular Activities.

The algorithmic theme of the iterations was extensive usage of boolean operations (intersection and difference) on polygons to derive interesting composite shapes.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: Splinter #188
metadata.description:
This release marks my first anniversary on the fx(hash) platform! I want to extend a huge thank you to everyone for a fantastic year, and I'm looking forward to many more in the generative-art world!

The basic algorithm is an evolution of the one I used in my first release, Raked Strokes. Instead of mimicking a brush with parallel segments, I'm using perpendicular line segments to define the overall abstract shape and then drawing each line in a simulated media. This approach blends my first attempts at natural media with everything I've learned in the past year.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press 's' to save a screenshot. The image size is 2357x3000px
Press 'p' to pause/resume during drawing.

Features
- Base path shape: line, circle, diamond, or rectangle
- Elements defining the spacing and orientation of the line segments
- The base path painted in the background
- Monochrome, dark background, and selection of palettes
- Ink pen styling: thickness, quality, and background blocking
- Paint styling: color distribution, quality
- Shapes: triangle, polygons, criteria for insertion
- Shapes overdrawing: outlines or perpendicular segments

metadata.name: Hydro Gen #77
metadata.description:
Against the backdrop of texts about valuing water, Hydro Gen charts the ecological devastation and eventual revival of the Tisza river following what has been called one of the gravest environmental disasters in central Europe since Chernobyl.

Nature and humans here are bound within a single frame — havoc in the ecological system activates the breakdown of meaning in the human signifying system of language, but hidden in the wave of ecological disaster is a (re)generative love poem to water that bears witness to its multifaceted beauty and power. A second poem is generated as a soundtrack based on the displayed background text.

- - - - - CLICK TO START SOUND - - - - -

Hydro Gen is a collaborative work conceptualized and developed over the course of one week as part of NFT DEB Generative Dimensions 2022 Hackathon and Conference.

Kalen Iwamoto, lead artist, director

Vitalii Shumanskyi, lead programmer

Nayven Vignette, audio programmer

Tamás Béke, data analysis and visualization

metadata.name: Ode to Bugs and Happy Accidents #122
metadata.description:
“If debugging is the process of removing software bugs, then programming must be the process of putting them in.”

― Edsger W. Dijkstra


This artwork is dedicated to happy accidents, mistakes, and bugs. Every key part of it is based on some sort of failure: wrong variable value, unstopped recursion, untimely function call. And sometimes it leads to pleasant results.

It was created to celebrate #fxhashturnsone event.

The earnings are partly donated to:
- Processing Foundation
- #TezosStandsWithUkraine

metadata.name: Pixel Blobs II #363
metadata.description:
This is a "zero player game" partially inspired by Conway's Game of Life. Between 4-10 pixel blobs are places on a screen and autonomously grow based on a deterministic set of rules. The game ends when all of the available cells are occupied by a blob. Some blobs prefer to slowly expand evenly in every direction. Other blobs prefer to aggressively push all of their energy into a single direction gobbling up as much territory as possible.

There is no single "victory condition". Maybe you care about the conquest of a single blob controlling as much space or energy as possible. Or maybe you prefer blobs to collaborate to create beautiful chaotic patterns.

Controls:
- 's' Saves a PNG of the current screen.
- 'i' Restarts the game in "infinite mode". 10 seconds after each game ends, the rules are shuffled and the game resets.

metadata.name: Pixel Blobs #273
metadata.description:
Each design features a preconfigured pattern of pixel blobs that slowly consume the canvas creating abstract pixel art. Canvases are also interactive and allow designers to create their own abstract art.

- 'c' clears the canvas
- click and drag to paint pixel blob pattern
- '0-9' changes the paint color
- 'ENTER' allows blobs to grow until the canvas is covered
- 'SPACE' pauses growth
- 'g' toggles grid lines on/off
- 's' saves the canvas as a png to mint or share

Pixel Blobs is a collaboration with Austin Pocus.

Coming soon: We're developing an interactive game based on Pixel Blobs. Follow @RasterlyNFT on Twitter for more details.

metadata.name: SPOT #134
metadata.description:
A study of circles, sizes, lines, colors, grains and alphas. The composition consists solely of 2d shapes but generates a 3d look. The base colors use a random chromaticity factor which results in a wild range of combinations. There is a 70% change on a dark background and 30% on a light background also 15% change on black and white. 

Press s in live mode for a 2000x2800 download

Download a higher resolution by adding to the URL:
&density=2 / &density=3 / &density=4

Lammetje December 2022

metadata.name: Dithered Gradients #395
metadata.description:
Each Dithered Gradient is generated from an algorithm derived from Pixel Blobs II. Pixels are initially placed onto a canvas in 4 orderly patterns. Every color grows in a deterministic pattern randomly generated before the canvas initializes. Interesting dither patterns are created when 2 colors collide.

Features:
- Saturation: (None=75%, +25%=18.75%, -25%=6.25%)
- Inverted Colors: (true=75%, false=25%)
- Pattern: (Horizontal=75%, Vertical=22.5%, X=1.875%, Box=.625%)

Co-released in partnership with fauxjebus May 10, 2022

metadata.name: Kāra-Lāmah #20
metadata.description:
Arabic calligraphy breaths life into words and images. It allows us to discover a sacred gesture, a moment of synchronization between mind and body.

This artwork is a tribute to the Arabic script. It's a generative version of a Kāra-Lāmah or 'Rough Draft'; a practice sheet where the calligrapher would practice her/his penmanship to perfect it but also to try different nibs of the qalam, or reed pen.

It uses glyphs from the Arabic (U+0600..U+06FF), Arabic Supplement (U+0750..U+077F) and Arabic Extended-A & B (U+08A0..U+08FF | U+0870..U+089F) Unicode blocks, the 'Scheherazade New' font and p5.js.

metadata.name: Asterium #259
metadata.description:
Asterium is a token that will grow with you, for an entire year. Changing and morphing over time to eventually reach its equilibrium.

It is a token where I try to symbolize the journey of life.
Where looking back is the best way to look forward.
Where looking into the future is not a possibility.
Where each day is as uncertain as the next.

A token that will surprise you and have its ups and downs as it grows over time.



Pricing:
Dutch auction 64-16-8, where anybody that picks one up at 64 tez gets a print of how their galaxy looks on any day from the present to day 0. Meaning you can claim the print at any point in the future.

The print will be printed on high quality hahnemühle torchon paper at 30x40 cm (11.81 x 15.75 in). Printed at a local print shop here in Utrecht. This paper has a rough texture to it that matches the textures of space perfectly.



Usage:
- Hover over your Asterium to view the name, date, days passed, status and render stats.
- Double press to export the current frame as a .png image.
- Use the slider at the bottom to scroll back in time to the days before today, you can go as far back as day 0 and as far forwards as today.
- The token refreshes every hour, so framing it in a digital picture frame is totally possible!
